<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="69" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
The 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. perpusilla" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="perpusilla">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">P. perpusilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group includes at least seven closely related species in Europe, separable only by small details of male terminalia (
<bibRefCitation author="Chandler, P" journalOrPublisher="Zapateri" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="1 - 24" refId="B6" refString="Chandler, P, Blasco-Zumeta, J, 2001. The fungus gnats (Diptera, Bolitophilidae, Keroplatidae and Mycetophilidae) of the Monegros Region (Zaragoza, Spain) and five other new European species of Pyratula Edwards and Sciophila Meigen. Zapateri 9: 1 - 24" title="The fungus gnats (Diptera, Bolitophilidae, Keroplatidae and Mycetophilidae) of the Monegros Region (Zaragoza, Spain) and five other new European species of Pyratula Edwards and Sciophila Meigen." volume="9" year="2001">Chandler and Blasco-Zumeta 2001</bibRefCitation>
). The studied Georgian specimens have the ventroapical margin of the gonocoxite with setose lobe (= without asetose protuberance) that is shared by three species, viz. 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. perpusilla" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="perpusilla">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">P. perpusilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. alpicola" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="alpicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">P. alpicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Chandler, 2001 and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. oracula" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="oracula">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">P. oracula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Chandler, 1994. The aedeagal complex is considerably short (elongate in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. oracula" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="oracula">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">P. oracula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and the aedeagal sheath is interrupted medially on the ventral side (with complete bridge in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. alpicola" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="alpicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">P. alpicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). However, the Georgian specimens are slightly different from 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. perpusilla" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="perpusilla">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">P. perpusilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as figured by 
<bibRefCitation author="Chandler, P" journalOrPublisher="Zapateri" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="1 - 24" refId="B6" refString="Chandler, P, Blasco-Zumeta, J, 2001. The fungus gnats (Diptera, Bolitophilidae, Keroplatidae and Mycetophilidae) of the Monegros Region (Zaragoza, Spain) and five other new European species of Pyratula Edwards and Sciophila Meigen. Zapateri 9: 1 - 24" title="The fungus gnats (Diptera, Bolitophilidae, Keroplatidae and Mycetophilidae) of the Monegros Region (Zaragoza, Spain) and five other new European species of Pyratula Edwards and Sciophila Meigen." volume="9" year="2001">Chandler and Blasco-Zumeta (2001</bibRefCitation>
: Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Habitus of Georgian fungus gnats of the families Bolitophilidae (A), Keroplatidae (B) and Mycetophilidae (C-I) A Bolitophila (Bolitophila) basicornis (Mayer, 1951) B Orfelia georgica Kurina &amp; Juergenstein, 2013 C Acnemia nitidicollis (Meigen, 1818) D Monoclona rufilatera (Walker, 1837) E Azana (Azana) anomala (Staeger, 1840) F Phthinia hyrcanica Zaitzev, 1984 G Neoempheria striata (Meigen, 1818) H Neoempheria brevilineata Okada, 1939 I Mycomya (Mycomya) marginata (Meigen, 1818)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1026.63749.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/524680" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">9</figureCitation>
- 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figure 12. Habitus of Georgian fungus gnats of the family Mycetophilidae A Allodiopsis domestica (Meigen, 1830) B Rymosia affinis Winnertz, 1863 C Brevicornu griseicolle (Staeger, 1840) D Cordyla fissa Edwards, 1925 E Anatella longisetosa Dziedzicki, 1923 F Mycetophila magnicauda Strobl, 1895 G Epicypta scatophora (Perris, 1849) H Phronia tenuis Winnertz, 1863 I Sceptonia tenuis Edwards, 1925 J Zygomyia humeralis (Wiedemann, 1817) K Dynatosoma reciprocum (Walker, 1848)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1026.63749.figure12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/524683" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">12</figureCitation>
) in having the distal dorsal corner of the aedeagal seath with a blunt protuberance that is otherwise typical to 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. alpicola" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="alpicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">P. alpicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The material was compared to that of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. alpicola" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="alpicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">P. alpicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. oracula" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="oracula">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">P. oracula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from North 
<collectingCountry name="Italy">Italy</collectingCountry>
(cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Kurina, O" editor="Ziegler, J" journalOrPublisher="Supplements" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="245 - 293" refId="B28" refString="Kurina, O, 2008b. Sciaroidea excl. Sciaridae. In: Ziegler, J, Ed., Diptera Stelviana. A dipterological perspective on a changing alpine landscape (Vol. 1). Studia Dipterologica. Supplements 16: 245 - 293" title="Sciaroidea excl. Sciaridae." volume="16" volumeTitle="Diptera Stelviana. A dipterological perspective on a changing alpine landscape (Vol. 1). Studia Dipterologica." year="2008 b">Kurina 2008b</bibRefCitation>
) and, pending a further molecular study of this species-group, is considered to be conspecific with 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. perpusilla" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="perpusilla">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">P. perpusilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
